               <msContents>
                  <summary>An account of knidia, probably of wine. It consists of a list of names, each followed by a measure. A second hand has added a third column consisting of sums in nomismata, which may represent either aditional cash payments or, more likely, the approximate cash value of the knidia. Except in lines 406 there is a general correspondence between the number of knidia and that of solidi.</summary>
                  <msItemStruct>
                     <note type="general">Location: Ann Arbor</note>
                     <note type="general">Pub. status: Recto; Verso is blank</note>
                     <textLang mainLang="cop">Coptic</textLang>
                  </msItemStruct>
               </msContents>
               <physDesc>
                  <objectDesc>
                     <supportDesc>
                        <support>1 papyrus ; 12.3 x 13 cm</support>
                        <condition>
                           <ab type="conservation">The papyrus itself, which almost forms a square, is well preserved. The final column is badly faded. There is collesis of about 2 cm in breadth in the left hand side of the papyrus</ab>
                        </condition>
                     </supportDesc>
                     <layoutDesc>
                        <layout>
                           <ab type="lines">11 lines</ab>
                           <ab type="recto-verso">Source of description: Recto</ab>
                        </layout>
                     </layoutDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  <handDesc>
                     <p>Dashes are used between the name and the amount of product or payment (cf. The same use in CPR IX 44.2n and P.Lond. V 1653.2n). A curving stroke intervenes between the eta and nu of "mena". This seems to be merely a careless slip made by the scribe while forming the letter B(eta) in the line above.</p>
                  </handDesc>
